      <exercise label="TaC-conic-4">
        <!-- <webwork xml:id="webwork-TaC-conic-4">
            <pg-code>
            </pg-code> -->
            <statement>
              <p>
                Explain why the following is true:
                <q>If the coefficient of the <m>x^2</m> term in the equation of an ellipse in standard form is smaller than the coefficient of the <m>y^2</m> term,
                then the ellipse has a horizontal major axis.</q>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                With the equation <m>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2}+\frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2}=1</m>,
                the ellipse has a horizontal major axis if <m>a \gt b</m>.
                But the coefficient of the <m>x^2</m> term is <m>1/a^2</m>
                (not <m>a^2</m>),
                so if <m>1/a^2\lt 1/b^2</m>, then <m>a \gt b</m> and the major axis is horizontal.
              </p>
            </solution>
        <!-- </webwork> -->
      </exercise>

      <exercise label="TaC-conic-5">
        <!-- <webwork xml:id="webwork-TaC-conic-5">
